Sure. Here's the same logical event ("user creates a new customer") represented in each of the common schemas. Notice that the actual business data is very similar—it's mostly the field names and organization that differ.

### 1. Elastic Common Schema (ECS)

ECS is probably the most widely adopted if you're using the Elastic stack, but it's also used outside of it.

```json
{
  "@timestamp": "2026-07-01T14:32:15.123Z",
  "log.level": "INFO",
  "message": "Customer created successfully",

  "service.name": "customer-api",
  "service.version": "2.4.1",
  "service.environment": "production",

  "event.category": "database",
  "event.type": "creation",
  "event.action": "create_customer",
  "event.outcome": "success",

  "trace.id": "4bf92f3577b34da6a3ce929d0e0e4736",
  "transaction.id": "6d8b9c4f2a",

  "user.id": "user-123",
  "user.name": "alice@example.com",

  "http.request.method": "POST",
  "url.path": "/customers",

  "labels": {
    "customerType": "enterprise",
    "source": "web"
  },

  "customer.id": "cust-456"
}
```

